    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="1102"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1102">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114 Mail/12–2144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Huddle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-21T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 21, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8254. American Interests—Japan—Prisoners of War Mail. Your 4107, December 5.
                    Foreign Office note December 19 quotes following message December 15 from Gorgé
                    (translation from French): <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“According to Japanese Foreign Office, mail for United States and
                            possessions will henceforth be directly addressed according agreement
                            with Soviet authorities to New York via Moscow-Tehran. Mail will be sent
                            from Shimonoseki in American postal bags and Japanese request United
                            States return Japanese postal bags forwarded United States before war.
                            Mail from America via Moscow has already reached Japan.”<note n="43"
                                xml:id="d1102fn43">In telegram 92, January 5, 1945, to Bern, the
                                Department stated that mail for the Far East would be despatched in
                                Japanese postal bags (711.94114 Mail/12–2144).</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huddle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
